Attribution

You must preserve all copyright notices and license terms.
Any distribution, addon, extension, patch, modpack inclusion,
or derivative work must credit the licensor and project in at
least one public-facing location (README, mod page, download
description, or credits screen):

    xlibs by Damian Sirbu
    https://github.com/damiansirbu-stalker

Credit must be reasonably prominent (not hidden in a nested
folder or obfuscated) and included wherever you list other mod
authors or dependencies. For modpacks, preserving the
software's own README and license files satisfies this
requirement. Omitting or removing attribution is a violation
of these terms.

Attribution does not authorize competing substitutes.

Noncompete

Any purpose is permitted, except providing a competing
substitute. A product is a competing substitute if it
reproduces substantial portions of the software's
implementation and:

  (a) is marketed as an alternative or replacement for
      the software and provides substantially the same
      core functionality without requiring the software, or

  (b) provides substantially the same core functionality
      as a standalone product without requiring the
      software, or

  (c) is intended to let users avoid installing the software
      while reproducing substantial portions of its
      implementation, or

  (d) ports or reproduces the software's implementation in
      another game, engine, or platform. Authorization for
      ports requires prior written permission from the licensor.

This applies regardless of price or whether credit is given.

Independent implementations that do not reproduce substantial
portions of the software's implementation are not competing
substitutes under these terms.

The following are not competing substitutes:

  - Mods that require the software to be installed
  - Integrations that call the software's public API
  - Modpacks that include the software with or without
    configuration overrides
  - Mods that extend the software through its documented
    extension points

For commercial licensing or exceptions, contact the licensor.

Addons and Extensions

An addon or extension is a work that (a) requires the software
to function and (b) does not provide a replacement
implementation of the software's core systems. Addons,
extensions, compatibility patches, translations, and
complementary works are permitted, provided they comply with
Attribution.

Non-Replication

You may not copy, adapt, or create derivative works that
reproduce substantial portions of the software's
implementation, including its specific combination of data
structures, API design, internal interfaces, private field
names, module organization, and code patterns, except as
permitted under this license. These elements as expressed in
the software are original work, even where individual
techniques exist elsewhere.

If you publish a derivative work, port, or implementation
based on the software, you must comply with both Attribution
and Noncompete. Attribution alone does not authorize works
that are competing substitutes.

Accessing and replicating internal implementation details --
including private field names, state reset values, internal
data formats, and undocumented module behavior -- constitutes
derivation under this section, even if accessed through public
runtime mechanisms.

The software's documentation may be used to create addons and
extensions that depend on the software. Documentation may not
be used as a blueprint to reproduce the software's
implementation as a standalone replacement.

Reverse Engineering

You may not reverse engineer, decompile, disassemble, or
otherwise analyze the internal implementation of the software
for the purpose of copying or reproducing the software's
implementation in other software.

This includes accessing internal module state, private fields,
or undocumented interfaces through reflection, dynamic lookup,
debug facilities, or any other mechanism, for the purpose of
reproducing implementation details in other software.

Analyzing the software to develop, debug, secure, or optimize
addons and extensions that depend on the software is permitted,
provided the result is not a competing substitute. Checking
whether a module is loaded for compatibility purposes is
permitted.

Automated Analysis

You may not use artificial intelligence, large language models,
code analysis tools, or other automated systems to extract or
reproduce substantial portions of the software's
implementation in other software.

Using such tools to learn how to use the software's public API,
configure it, debug integrations, or develop addons and
extensions that depend on it is permitted.

Internal Interfaces

Functions, fields, state, and behavior not documented in the
software's public documentation or marked as public API are
internal interfaces. Accessing, replicating, or depending on
internal interfaces for the purpose of reproducing the
software's implementation or creating a competing substitute
is a violation of these terms, regardless of the access method.

Temporarily depending on internal interfaces to maintain
compatibility in addons that require the software is permitted,
provided it does not reproduce implementation or create a
competing substitute.

The software's public API consists of exported functions
documented in its README, architecture documentation, or
source code comments as intended for external use. In case of
ambiguity, only interfaces explicitly marked as public API in
the repository are public API.

